MWI: Compare ARC2 and CHIRPS

Seth Caldwell

13/09/2021

Initial data loading and wrangling

Alright, so first we need to load in the data that has already been processed. We have 3 files, one for CHIRPS data, and 2 for ARC2 data, all aggregated at the ADM2 level. All datasets contain dry spells identified through that particular dataset, and filtered to only occur during rainy seasons identified using CHIRPS data.

Since the rainy season definitions would slightly vary using ARC2 definitions, some of the dry spells recorded captured in those datasets may be instead the onset of the dry season and not captured if we defined the rainy season using ARC2 data. After some exploration, I found that for ARC2 dry spells with a duration > 30, for both the centroids and touching method, only a single one of those 20 and 18 dry spells respectively overlapped with a CHIRPS identified dry spell, and none had a dry spell confirmation in January or February. Thus, I explicitly filter these 38 dry spells out from the two methods prior to comparing the various dry spell identification methods.

# data loading

arc2_center_df <- read_csv(paste0(expl_dir, "/arc2/mwi_arc2_centroid_dry_spells_during_rainy_season.csv"),
                           col_types = "_ccDDDdd") %>%
  select(pcode,
         ADM2_EN,
         arc2_center_start = dry_spell_first_date,
         arc2_center_confirmation = dry_spell_confirmation,
         arc2_center_end = dry_spell_last_date,
         arc2_center_duration = dry_spell_duration) %>%
  filter(arc2_center_duration <= 30)

arc2_touch_df <- read_csv(paste0(expl_dir, "/arc2/mwi_arc2_touching_dry_spells_during_rainy_season.csv"),
                          col_types = "_ccDDDd") %>%
  select(pcode,
         ADM2_EN,
         arc2_touch_start = dry_spell_first_date,
         arc2_touch_confirmation = dry_spell_confirmation,
         arc2_touch_end = dry_spell_last_date,
         arc2_touch_duration = dry_spell_duration) %>%
  filter(arc2_touch_duration <= 30)

chirps_df <- read_csv(paste0(
  process_dir, 
  "/dry_spells/v1/archive/dry_spells_during_rainy_season_list_2000_2020_mean_back.csv"
)) %>%
  transmute(pcode,
            ADM2_EN,
            chirps_start = dry_spell_first_date,
            chirps_confirmation = dry_spell_first_date + 13,
            chirps_end = dry_spell_last_date,
            chirps_duration = dry_spell_duration) %>%
  filter(str_detect(pcode, "MW3"))

With the 3 separate datasets loaded, we can use the fuzzyjoin package to join the datasets together (with some repititive filtering after) to capture all overlapping dry spells to examine in detail how the 3 separate methods for dry spell identification compare for each incident in particular.

# joining ARC2 touch and center dry spells to get all overlaps

arc2_center_lj1 <- fuzzy_full_join(
  arc2_center_df,
  arc2_touch_df,
  match_fun = list(`==`, `>=`, `<=`),
  by = c(
    "pcode" = "pcode",
    "arc2_center_start" = "arc2_touch_start",
    "arc2_center_start" = "arc2_touch_end"
  ))

arc2_center_lj2 <- fuzzy_full_join(
  arc2_center_df,
  arc2_touch_df,
  match_fun = list(`==`, `>=`, `<=`),
  by = c(
    "pcode" = "pcode",
    "arc2_center_end" = "arc2_touch_start",
    "arc2_center_end" = "arc2_touch_end"
  ))

arc2_center_lj3 <- fuzzy_full_join(
  arc2_touch_df,
  arc2_center_df,
  match_fun = list(`==`, `>=`, `<=`),
  by = c(
    "pcode" = "pcode",
    "arc2_touch_end" = "arc2_center_start",
    "arc2_touch_end" = "arc2_center_end"
  ))

arc2_center_lj4 <- fuzzy_full_join(
  arc2_touch_df,
  arc2_center_df,
  match_fun = list(`==`, `>=`, `<=`),
  by = c(
    "pcode" = "pcode",
    "arc2_touch_start" = "arc2_center_start",
    "arc2_touch_start" = "arc2_center_end"
  ))

arc2_overlap_df <- bind_rows(arc2_center_lj1,
                             arc2_center_lj2,
                             arc2_center_lj3,
                             arc2_center_lj4) %>%
  mutate(pcode.x = ifelse(is.na(pcode.x), pcode.y, pcode.x)) %>%
  select(-starts_with("ADM2")) %>%
  rename(pcode = pcode.x) %>%
  select(-pcode.y) %>%
  distinct() %>%
  group_by(pcode, arc2_center_start) %>%
  filter(!(n() > 1 & is.na(arc2_touch_start))) %>% # drop duplicate row of center
  ungroup()

# now joining with CHIRPS to get additional overlaps

arc2_chirps_lj1 <- fuzzy_full_join(

arc2_chirps_lj3 <- fuzzy_full_join(

  by = c(
    "pcode" = "pcode",

arc2_chirps_lj4 <- fuzzy_full_join(

  match_fun = list(`==`, `>=`, `<=`),
  by = c(
    "pcode" = "pcode",

arc2_chirps_df <- bind_rows(arc2_chirps_lj1,
                            arc2_chirps_lj2,
                            arc2_chirps_lj3,
                            arc2_chirps_lj4,
                            arc2_chirps_lj5,
                            arc2_chirps_lj6,
                            arc2_chirps_lj7,
                            arc2_chirps_lj8) %>%
  mutate(pcode.x = ifelse(is.na(pcode.x), pcode.y, pcode.x)) %>%
  rename(pcode = pcode.x) %>%
  select(-pcode.y, -starts_with("ADM2_EN")) %>% 
  distinct() %>%
  # clean up duplicate joined rows
  group_by(pcode, arc2_center_start, arc2_touch_start) %>%
  filter(!(n() > 1 & is.na(chirps_start) & !is.na(arc2_center_start) & !is.na(arc2_touch_start))) %>%
  group_by(pcode, arc2_center_start, chirps_start) %>%
  filter(!(n() > 1 & is.na(arc2_touch_start) & !is.na(arc2_center_start) & !is.na(chirps_start))) %>%
  group_by(pcode, chirps_start, arc2_touch_start) %>%
  filter(!(n() > 1 & is.na(arc2_center_start) & !is.na(chirps_start) & !is.na(arc2_touch_start))) %>%
  group_by(pcode, chirps_start) %>%
  filter(!(n() > 1 & is.na(arc2_center_start) & !is.na(chirps_start))) %>%
  ungroup()

# get simple ADM2_EN data set
adm2_df <- map(list(
  arc2_center_df,
  arc2_touch_df,
  chirps_df
), ~ select(.x, pcode, ADM2_EN)) %>%
  bind_rows() %>%
  distinct()

# add ADM2_EN to main data frame
arc2_chirps_df <- arc2_chirps_df %>%
  left_join(adm2_df, by = "pcode")

Simple comparison

At a basic level, we detect about 1/3 more dry spells using ARC2 data than using CHIRPS data, with 61 and 60 detected with the centroid and touching methods respectively, and only 42 using CHIRPS. Let’s compare how and when dry spells are detected by each method.

arc2_chirps_df <- mutate(arc2_chirps_df,
  chirps_ds = !is.na(chirps_confirmation),
  arc2_centroid_ds = !is.na(arc2_center_confirmation),
  arc2_touch_ds = !is.na(arc2_touch_confirmation)
)

arc2_chirps_df %>%
  select(CHIRPS = chirps_ds,
         `ARC2 (Centroid)` = arc2_centroid_ds,
         `ARC2 (Touching)` = arc2_touch_ds) %>%
  group_by_all() %>%
  summarize(Occurrences = n(),
            .groups = "drop") %>%
  mutate(across(-Occurrences, ~ ifelse(.x, "Detected", "Not detected"))) %>%
  arrange(desc(Occurrences)) %>%
  knitr::kable()
CHIRPS ARC2 (Centroid) ARC2 (Touching) Occurrences
Detected Detected Detected 29
Not detected Detected Detected 26
Detected Not detected Not detected 13
Not detected Not detected Detected 11
Not detected Detected Not detected 8

We can see above a breakdown of dry spell detection by method. Interestingly, where CHIRPS detects a dry spells, both ARC2 methods either also detect one or don’t. We should be comfortable just comparing CHIRPS dry spells to a single ARC2 method given these similarities.

From above, we can see that the dry spell detection using CHIRPS always detects the dry spell after it has been detected by ARC2. This is reassuring news for the switch to ARC2 for the observational trigger. However, what does it look like where CHIRPS has data and ARC2 is missing it?

Trigger activation

Given that the 2 ARC2 methods are so similar, we likely only need to look at the centroid method. Daily value comparisons

First, let’s do some 2d histograms to examine the distribution of various calculation methods. What do we see between the centroid and touching raster methods applied?

daily_df %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = arc2_centroid,
             y = arc2_touch)) +
  stat_bin2d(aes(fill = log(..density..)),
             bins = 200) +
  theme_bw() +
  geom_abline(intercept = 0) +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  labs(title = "2D histogram, log scale",
       x = "ARC2 (centroid) precipitation",
       y = "ARC2 (touching) precipitation")

While it looks like the touching method might skew higher (if just slightly) at higher levels of rainfall, we are more concerned at their behavior at lower levels.

daily_df %>%
  filter(arc2_centroid <= 1 | arc2_touch <= 1) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = arc2_centroid,
             y = arc2_touch)) +
  geom_bin2d(bins = 50,
             aes(fill = log(..density..))) +
  theme_bw() +
  geom_abline(intercept = 0) +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  labs(title = "2D histogram, log scale",
       subtitle = "Only dates where at least one metric measures <= 0.2mm",
       x = "ARC2 (centroid) precipitation",
       y = "ARC2 (touching) precipitation")

And above we can see that the centroid method in general trends much higher at these levels. This intuitively makes sense as the touching method takes the average of more raster cells than the centroid method, so will tend to regress toward the mean at the extremes. Anyway, given their similar results in identifying dry spells and the results above, should be fine to simply compare the centroid method against CHIRPS and not the touching method.

daily_df %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = arc2_centroid,
             y = chirps)) +

       x = "ARC2 (centroid) precipitation",
       y = "CHIRPS precipitation")

daily_df %>%

### January / February comparisons

Since our action trigger will be monitored only in January and February 2022, important to validate the comparability of ARC2 and CHIRPS across that period solely to ensure the broader trends still hold true (which indicate that ARC2 is as sufficient if not preferable for dry spell detection).

daily_df %>%
  mutate(chirps_arc2_diff = chirps - arc2_centroid) %>%
  filter(lubridate::month(date) <= 2) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = chirps_arc2_diff)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 60) +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(title = "Precipitation difference, CHIRPS - ARC2",
       subtitle = "January and February only",
       x = "Chirps - ARC2",
       y = "Count")

daily_df %>%
  mutate(chirps_arc2_diff = chirps - arc2_centroid) %>%
  filter(arc2_centroid <= 0.2 | chirps <= 0.2,
         lubridate::month(date) <= 2) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = chirps_arc2_diff)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 60) +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(title = "Precipitation difference, CHIRPS - ARC2",
       subtitle = "January and February only; only dates where at least one metric measures <= 0.2mm",
       x = "Chirps - ARC2",
       y = "Count")

We can again see that CHIRPS data in this period does indeed follow the same trend.

During mismatched dry spells

Another final piece of checking to do would be to see what is going on with daily values in the periods where one method detects a dry spell but the other detects no overlapping dry spell at all.

arc2_no_spell_daily <- arc2_chirps_df %>%
  filter(chirps_ds, !arc2_centroid_ds) %>%
  mutate(ds_uid = paste(pcode, lubridate::year(chirps_confirmation), sep = ", ")) %>%
  fuzzy_inner_join(
    daily_df,
    match_fun = list(`==`, `<=`, `>=`),
    by = c(
      "pcode" = "pcode",
      "chirps_start" = "date",
      "chirps_end" = "date"
    )) %>%
  select(pcode = pcode.x,
         ds_uid,
         date,
         chirps,
         arc2_centroid)

arc2_no_spell_daily %>%
  mutate(chirps_arc2_diff = chirps - arc2_centroid) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = chirps_arc2_diff)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 60) +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(title = "Precipitation difference, CHIRPS - ARC2",
       subtitle = "Only dates where CHIRPS detected a dry spell but none was detected by ARC2",
       x = "Chirps - ARC2",
       y = "Count")

Clearly, by defining our subset, we see many instances where the CHIRPS measured precipitation is lower than ARC2. But where is actually coming about?

arc2_no_spell_daily %>%
  mutate(chirps_arc2_diff = chirps - arc2_centroid,
         chirps_type = ifelse(chirps > 0, "> 0mm", "0mm"),
         ) %>%
  group_by(chirps_type) %>%
  summarize(`ARC2 0mm` = sum(arc2_centroid == 0, na.rm = T),
            `ARC2 > 0mm` = sum(arc2_centroid > 0, na.rm = T),
            `ARC2 > 0mm & > chirps` = sum(arc2_centroid > 0 & arc2_centroid > chirps, na.rm = T))
## # A tibble: 2 × 4
##   chirps_type `ARC2 0mm` `ARC2 > 0mm` `ARC2 > 0mm & > chirps`
##   <chr>            <int>        <int>                   <int>
## 1 > 0mm               15            9                       5
## 2 0mm                115           12                      12

From the above, it’s clear that the vast majority of the time, ARC2 and CHIRPS align, just that there are instances where CHIRPS measures 0 precipitation but ARC2 measures some, and another 8 where both ARC2 and CHIRPS measure precipitation but CHIRPS measures none.

arc2_no_spell_daily %>%
  filter(!is.na(arc2_centroid)) %>%
  group_by(ds_uid) %>%
  arrange(date, .by_group = TRUE) %>%
  mutate(id = row_number()) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = id)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = chirps), color = "grey") +
  geom_line(aes(y = arc2_centroid)) +
  facet_wrap(~ds_uid, scales = "free") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank()) +
  labs(x = "Days of dry spell",
       y = "Precipitation",
       title = "Precipitation values of ARC2 and CHIRPS during CHIRPS dry spells",
       subtitle = "ARC2 values in black")

Aha! Very informative! It’s quite clear that in all but one of the dry spells, ARC2 is measuring “extreme” spikes in precipitation surrounding primarily days with none. In some instances, like MW209 or MW203, these are spikes also measured by CHIRPS, just with higher precipitation recorded by ARC2. In the majority, however, the spikes are registered solely by ARC2, whereas CHIRPS records little to no precipitation.

Note that the MW310 2020 graph shows no overlapping dry spell because the ARC2 detected a dry spell that was over 200 days and was thus removed during filtering.

Flip it!

Just for a bit of extra exploration, let’s quickly run the same code to assess CHIRPS daily values where CHIRPS doesn’t detect an overlapping dry spell when ARC2 detects one.

chirps_no_spell_daily <- arc2_chirps_df %>%
  filter(!chirps_ds, arc2_centroid_ds) %>%
  mutate(ds_uid = paste(pcode, lubridate::year(arc2_center_confirmation), sep = ", ")) %>%
  fuzzy_inner_join(
    daily_df,
    match_fun = list(`==`, `<=`, `>=`),
    by = c(
      "pcode" = "pcode",
      "arc2_center_start" = "date",
      "arc2_center_end" = "date"
    )) %>%
  select(pcode = pcode.x,
         ds_uid,
         date,
         chirps,
         arc2_centroid)

chirps_no_spell_daily %>%
  mutate(chirps_arc2_diff = chirps - arc2_centroid) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = chirps_arc2_diff)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 60) +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(title = "Precipitation difference, CHIRPS - ARC2",
       subtitle = "Only dates where CHIRPS detected a dry spell but none was detected by ARC2",
       x = "Chirps - ARC2",
       y = "Count")

chirps_no_spell_daily %>%
  mutate(chirps_arc2_diff = chirps - arc2_centroid,
         arc2_type = ifelse(arc2_centroid > 0, "> 0mm", "0mm"),
         ) %>%
  group_by(arc2_type) %>%
  summarize(`CHIRPS 0mm` = sum(chirps == 0, na.rm = T),
            `CHIRPS > 0mm` = sum(chirps > 0, na.rm = T),
            `CHIRPS > 0mm & > chirps` = sum(chirps > 0 & chirps > arc2_centroid, na.rm = T))
## # A tibble: 2 × 4
##   arc2_type `CHIRPS 0mm` `CHIRPS > 0mm` `CHIRPS > 0mm & > chirps`
##   <chr>            <int>          <int>                     <int>
## 1 > 0mm               12             32                        30
## 2 0mm                423             93                        93
chirps_no_spell_daily %>%
  group_by(ds_uid) %>%
  arrange(date, .by_group = TRUE) %>%
  mutate(id = row_number()) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = id)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = chirps)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = arc2_centroid), color = "grey") +
  facet_wrap(~ds_uid, scales = "free", ncol = 5) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank()) +
  labs(x = "Days of dry spell",
       y = "Precipitation",
       title = "Precipitation values of ARC2 and CHIRPS during ARC2 dry spells",
       subtitle = "CHIRPS values in black")

Contrary to ARC2 values were detecting dry spells, it looks like the CHIRPS data is not always just a singular spike, but often consistent measures of precipitation across the ARC2 identified dry spell.
